From Eric Ikhilae, Abuja  The Federal Government has begun the process of prosecuting a former Managing Director of the Pipelines and Products Marketing Company (PPMC), Haruna Momoh; his wife, Ochuko Okor Momoh and four others for their alleged complicity in N2.4 billion fraud. The government, through the Independent Corrupt Practices and Other Related Offences Commission (ICPC), has filed a 13-count charge before the Federal High Court in Abuja. The charge was filed on November 8, 2019 by an ICPC prosecutor Osuobeni Akponimisingha, who was said to have been assigned the matter. The Nation gathered that a prosecution team, to be led by Akponimisingha, has been constituted and is awaiting a signal from the Federal High Court, which is expected to issue a notice, indicating the date for arraignment. Others named in the charge are: the Company Secretary of Energopol Nigeria Limited, Blessing Azuka-Agozi; Blaid Construction Limited (where Mrs. Momoh is said to serve as Managing Director and Chief Executive Officer); Stanbic IBTC Bank Plc and Energopol Nigeria Limited. Momoh was, in count one, accused of using his position, as the MD of PPMC sometime in January 2013 “to confer unfair advantage on your wife, Mrs. Ochuko Okor Momoh by awarding a contract worth N249,319,070.00 to her company – Blaid Construction Limited – an offence punishable under Section 19 of the Corrupt Practices and Other Related Offences Act, 2000. In counts two, five and six, Mrs Momoh was alleged to have “indirectly received”, “knowingly converted” and “took possession” of N249,319,070.00 paid to her company by the PPMC, for the contract awarded to her company, while her husband was the MD of the PPMC. Mrs. Momoh was, in counts three and fou accused of refusing to honour invitations by investigators from the ICPC, an act said to be an offence and punishable under Section 28(10) of the Corrupt Practices and Other Related Offences Act, 2000. In count seven, Stanbic IBTC Bank Plc is accused of failing to report “suspicious and unjustifiable transactions” made on June 22, 2011 when 13 tranches of N10 million deposit were made into Blaid Construction Limited’s account with the bank in one day. This is an offence, according to the prosecutor, contrary to and punishable under sections 15(2)(d) and (3) of the Money Laundering (Prohibition) Act, 2011. The bank was also charged with similar offence in counts eight, nine and 10, where it was said to have failed to reports suspicious payment of N10 million in 46 tranches between March 12 and May 10, 2012; 14 tranches of N10 million deposit on August 15 and 16, 2013, and 24 tranches of N10 million deposit “on the same day, that is July 9, 2014 to May 10, 1012 (as shown in the account statement) into the account of Blaid Construction Limited domiciled with you (the bank).” In count 11, Energopol Nigeria Limited was said to have, between May 2012 and August 2015, “with intent to conceal proceeds of some unlawful activities, made cash payments, both in dollar and naira, to Blaid Construction Limited through Stanbic IBTC Bank Plc with account No: 9202474171 to the tune of N1.150 billion”. The offence, the prosecutor said, is contrary to and punishable under sections 15(2)(d) and (3) of the Money Laundering (Prohibition) Act, 2011. Blaid Construction is charged, in count 12, with concealing proceeds of unlawful act by allegedly accepting cash payments in dollar and naira “from Energopol Nig Ltd, through Stanbic IBTC with account number 9202474171 to the tune of N1.150 billion”. In count 13, Blessing Azuka-Agozi was charged with failing to provide ICPC’s investigators with relevant materials, including contract agreement, technical drawings, in relation to a purported contractual relationship between her company, Energopol and Blaid Construction, which informed the alleged cash payments. Also, Mr and Mrs Momoh and Blaid Construction have challenged the ex parte orders for interim forfeiture of some of their properties as granted the ICPC by Justice Olukayode Adeniyi of the High Court of the Federal Capital Territory (FCT) in Apo, Abuja. The court has scheduled hearing for November 14, 2019 in the application filed the Momohs, challenging the forfeiture orders. ICPC claimed, among others, that the move was part of its efforts to recover about N2,417,037,404 and landed properties, which the Momohs allegedly acquired unlawfully. The commission claimed that the money includes foreign and local currencies stashed in multiple accounts in four different banks as well as five landed properties located in different parts of Abuja metropolis.